    "narrative": "For today\u2019s slate, **Vinnie Pasquantino** and **Tyler Soderstrom** emerge as our premier offensive engines, each posting scores above 63. **Vinnie Pasquantino** draws a favorable matchup against the hittable Jeffrey Springs, and despite a slight penalty for the L/L matchup, his floor remains high enough to anchor the middle of the order. Meanwhile, **Tyler Soderstrom** benefits from a strong park factor and a soft SP_xERA of 4.33, effectively neutralizing his platoon disadvantage to provide the most efficient output of the day. While **Corbin Carroll** sits just below the 60-threshold, he remains a critical start; despite facing an elite arm in Brandon Woodruff, **Corbin Carroll**\u2019s aggressive base-running profile against a slow-delivery pitcher makes him a high-upside gamble for stolen bases, a category we cannot afford to concede.\n\nThe most difficult lineup decision today centered on **Brice Turang** and **James Wood**, both of whom hovered in the high 50s. **Brice Turang** ultimately held his spot over potential utility depth because his favorable matchup against Michael Soroka provides a better chance to reach base and capitalize on SB opportunities. We are forced to exercise caution with **Mickey Moniak** and **Kyle Karros**, both of whom are projected for moderate outcomes against Andrew Abbott. While **Kyle Karros** holds a slight efficiency edge due to platoon advantages, neither is a \"must-start\" if we were deeper at the position. With **Jazz Chisholm Jr.**, **Josh Naylor**, and **Jose Caballero** unavailable due to off-days, and **Giancarlo Stanton** sidelined on the IL, our roster flexibility is thin; we are forced to rely on the current lineup\u2019s ability to exploit these mid-tier matchups to maintain our pace in the 5x5 standings. Keep a close eye on final lineup confirmations for **Vinnie Pasquantino** and **James Wood**, as any drop in their projected batting order will necessitate a swift re-evaluation of their daily efficiency scores.",
